<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="ch1-What-is-a-DE" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>What is a Differential Equation?</title>

  <introduction>
    <p> Text before the first section. </p>
  </introduction>

<definition xml:id="def-DifferentialEquation"><idx>Differential Equations</idx>
    <statement>
    <p>
      An equation relating an unknown function and one or more of its derivatives is called a <term>differential equation</term>}(or DE for short).
    </p>
    <p>
      A DE in one independent variable is called an <term>ordinary differential equation</term> (short, ODE). A DE in several independent variables is called a <term>partial differential equation</term>(or PDE).
    </p>
    <p>
      The <term>order</term> of a differential equation is the order of the highest derivative of the unknown function in the equation.
    </p>
    </statement>
</definition>

<example xml:id="example-DEs">
    <title>Some Examples</title>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <m>\dfrac{dy}{dt}=y</m> is a <term>first-order</term> ODE in independent variable </m>t</m>.
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>\dfrac{\partial u}{\partial x}+\dfrac{\partial u}{\partial y}=0</m> is a <term>first-order</term> PDE in two independent variables, <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>y^{(3)}+xy'+y^2=e^{-x}</m> is a <term>third-order</term>  ODE in independent variable <m>x</m>.
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>u_{t}=u_{xx}+u_{yy}</m> is a <term>second-order</term> PDE in three independent variables <m>t</m>, <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> (this is a <term>two-dimensional heat equation</term>).
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
</example>

<note xml:id="note-deriv-notations">
  <title>Note</title>
  <p>
    The prior examples demonstrate various notations for derivatives.
  </p>
</note>

<p>
 Recall the following.  Let <m>y</m> be a function of <m>x</m>, so <m>>y = y(x)</m>.
 <ol>
  <li>
    For first derivatives, the notations <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}</m> and <m>y'</m> are equivalent.
  </li>
  <li>
    For higher order derivatives, the notations <m>\dfrac{d^n y}{dx^n}</m> and <m>y^{(n)}</m> are equivalent.
  </li>
 </ol>
</p>

<p>
  Let $u$ be a function of $x$ and $y$. So $u = u(x, y)$.  Then we may represent the partial derivatives by, for example:
  <me>
    \dfrac{\partial u}{\partial x} \text{ and } \dfrac{\partial^2 u}{\partial^2 y}
  </me>
  or, equivalently
  <me>
    u_x \text{ and } u_{yy}.$$
  </me>
</p>

<warning xml:id="warning-only-ODEs">
    <title>This book only deals with ODEs</title>
    <p>
      For the remainder of this textbook, we will only consider ordinary differential equations.
    </p>
  </warning>

<p>
The most general form of an <m>n^{\text{th}}</m>-order ordinary differential equation with independent variable <m>x</m> and unknown function (or dependent variable) <m>y=y(x)</m> is
<me xml:id="eq-general" number="yes">
  F\bigl(x,y,y',y'',\dots,y^{(n)}\bigr)=0,
</me>
where <m>F</m> is a function of the <m>n+2</m> variables.
</p>

<p>
An <m>n^{\text{th}}</m>-order differential equation solved relative to the highest derivative (which may not be possible) is said to be in <term>standard</term> (or <term>normal</term>) form:
<me xml:id="eq-normal" number="yes">
  y^{(n)}=f\bigl(x,y,y',y'',\dots,y^{(n-1)}\bigr),
</me>
where <m>f</m> is a function of the <m>n+1</m> variables <m>x, y, y', \dots, y^{(n)}</m>.
</p>

<p>Thus, in the prior examples, DE 1 is in standard form and DE 3 is not.</p>

<definition xml:id="def-solution">
  <title>Solution of a Differential Equation</title>  
  <statement>
    <p>
      A function <m>y=y(x)</m> is called a <term>solution</term><idx>solution</idx> of differential equation <xref ref="eq-general" /> on an interval <m>I</m> if it is <m>n</m> times differentiable on <m>I</m> and
      <md>
        F\bigl(x,y(x),y'(x),y''(x),...,y^{(n)}(x)\bigr)=0
      </md>
      for all <m>x\in I</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The function <m>y=y(x)</m> is also said to <term>satisfy</term><idx>satisfy</idx> differential equation <xref ref="eq-general" /> on the interval <m>I</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>

<example xml:id="example-iex" number="yes">
  <statement>
    <p>
      For any <m>c\in \R</m>, the function <m>y=ce^t</m> is a solution of the DE
      <me>
        \dfrac{dy}{dt}=y
      </me>
      on the interval <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m>      
    </p>
  </statement>
</example>

<section xml:id="sec-Exercises for Chapter 1">
  <title>Exercises for Chapter 1</title>
<ol>
  <li>
    Verify the solution in Example <xref ref="example-iex" />.
  </li>
  <li>
    Give an example of a differential equation whose solution is <m>y(x) = x^2-2</m> on <m>(-\infty, \infty)</m>.
  </li>
  <li>
    Give an example of a differential equation and its solution.
  </li>
</ol>
</section>

</chapter>